04687nam a22006735i 9781503603509DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2017000968  a97815036035097 a10.1515/97815036035092doi  a(DE-B1597)564271  a(OCoLC)1178769458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aRC627.B45bS45 2017 4aRC627.B45bS45 2017eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a610.9512231 aSmith, Hilary A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForgotten Disease :bIllnesses Transformed in Chinese Medicine /cHilary A. Smith. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. Foot Qi in Early Chinese Medicine -- tChapter two. Competing for Medical Authority over Disease -- tChapter three. Simplifying and Standardizing Disease -- tChapter four. The Northerner's Dietary Disorder -- tChapter five. Getting Rich and Getting Sick -- tChapter six. Creating Beriberi in Meiji Japan -- tChapter seven. Foot Qi's Multiple Meanings in Modern East Asia -- tConclusion -- tGlossary of Chinese Characters -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAround the turn of the twentieth century, disorders that Chinese physicians had been writing about for over a millennium acquired new identities in Western medicine-sudden turmoil became cholera; flowers of heaven became smallpox; and foot qi became beriberi. Historians have tended to present these new identities as revelations, overlooking evidence that challenges Western ideas about these conditions. In Forgotten Disease, Hilary A. Smith argues that, by privileging nineteenth century sources, we misrepresent what traditional Chinese doctors were seeing and doing, therefore unfairly viewing their medicine as inferior. Drawing on a wide array of sources, ranging from early Chinese classics to modern scientific research, Smith traces the history of one representative case, foot qi, from the fourth century to the present day. She examines the shifting meanings of disease over time, showing that each transformation reflects the social, political, intellectual, and economic environment. The breathtaking scope of this story offers insights into the world of early Chinese doctors and how their ideas about health, illness, and the body were developing far before the advent of modern medicine. Smith highlights the fact that modern conceptions of these ancient diseases create the impression that the West saved the Chinese from age-old afflictions, when the reality is that many prominent diseases in China were actually brought over as a result of imperialism. She invites the reader to reimagine a history of Chinese medicine that celebrates its complexity and nuance, rather than uncritically disdaining this dynamic form of healing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBeri-berizChinaxHistory. 0aFootxDiseaseszChinaxHistory. 0aMedical literaturezChinaxHistory. 0aMedicinezChinaxHistory. 4acognition. 4acognitive science of religion. 4adual processing. 4agods. 4ahuman brain/mind. 4ahuman evolution. 4amental modularity. 4anatural selection. 4areligious ideas. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360350940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603509.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2